05264nam a22007095i 9780226689289DE-B159720210526051534.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210526t20202020ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a2019037187  a97802266892897 a10.7208/97802266892892doi  a(DE-B1597)549372  a(OCoLC)1151182729  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL00aB2137b.B36 2020 4aB2137b.B36 2021 7aPHI0000002bisacsh04a848.5092231 aScott, John T., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aRousseau's Reader :bStrategies of Persuasion and Education /cJohn T. Scott. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (336 p.) :b9 halftones, 4 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAbbreviations -- tIntroduction -- tChapter 1. Appearance and Reality in the Discourse on the Sciences and the Arts -- tChapter 2. Picturing Natural Man in the Discourse on Inequality -- tChapter 3. The Education of the Reader in Emile -- tChapter 4. The Illustrative Education of Emile -- tChapter 5. The Narrative Frame of the “Profession of Faith” -- tChapter 6. Reading with Emile and Sophie -- tChapter 7. Reading the Social Contract -- tConclusion -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aOn his famous walk to Vincennes to visit the imprisoned Diderot, Rousseau had what he called an “illumination”—the realization that man was naturally good but becomes corrupted by the influence of society—a fundamental change in Rousseau’s perspective that would animate all of his subsequent works. At that moment, Rousseau “saw” something he had hitherto not seen, and he made it his mission to help his readers share that vision through an array of rhetorical and literary techniques. In Rousseau’s Reader, John T. Scott looks at the different strategies Rousseau used to engage and persuade the readers of his major philosophical works, including the Social Contract, Discourse on Inequality, and Emile. Considering choice of genre; textual structure; frontispieces and illustrations; shifting authorial and narrative voice; addresses to readers that alternately invite and challenge; apostrophe, metaphor, and other literary devices; and, of course, paradox, Scott explores how the form of Rousseau’s writing relates to the content of his thought and vice versa. Through this skillful interplay of form and content, Rousseau engages in a profoundly transformative dialogue with his readers. While most political philosophers have focused, understandably, on Rousseau’s ideas, Scott shows convincingly that the way he conveyed them is also of vital importance, especially given Rousseau’s enduring interest in education. Giving readers the key to Rousseau’s style, Scott offers fresh and original insights into the relationship between the substance of his thought and his literary and rhetorical techniques, which enhance our understanding of Rousseau’s project and the audiences he intended to reach.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 0aPhilosophy, Frenchy18th century. 7aPHILOSOPHY / General.2bisacsh  aEducation.  aEnlightenment.  aJean-Jacques Rousseau.  aLiterary Criticism.  aPersuasion.  aReading.  aRhetoric.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDTL Humanities 2020z978311073776908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Philosophy 2020 Englishz978311070482208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Philosophy 2020z9783110